fields.description:
The 1000G dataset can be used to remove common variants. As an example, the 5th percentile represents the variants that _only_ occur in 5% of the population. Note that 1000G data only applies to SNPs, so
applying this filter will only apply to SNPs.
fields.name: 1000G Allele Frequency

fields.description: Select a cohort to compare the proband's variants against. Then define an allele frequency threshold which will only include variants that are seen in the population percentage.
fields.name: Cohort

fields.description: The minimum possible allele frequency is bound by the number of samples in the cohort. For example, the minimum possible frequency for 8 samples would be 0.125, while for 100 would be 0.01.
fields.name: Cohort Allele Frequency

fields.description: The predicted impact of the variant.

fields.description: Region of the genome that is affected.
fields.name: Effect Region

fields.description: The minor-allele frequency in percent listed across all populations. These apply to SNPs only.
fields.name: EVS Allele Frequency

fields.description: For INDELs, A1, A2, or An refers to the N-th alternate allele while R refers to the reference allele.
fields.name: Observed Genotypes

fields.description: The greater the read depth, the greater confidence the base read is correct. Typically 30x coverage should be used for clinical analysis.
fields.name: Read Depth

fields.description: The following fields allow you to select different percentage ranges to limit to. These percentages are values in the range from 0.0 to 1.0. For example, if you wanted to select the frequencies between 25% and 50% you would enter 0.25 in the lower bound box and 0.5 in the upper bound box.
